# VoltLife Backend Foundation Implementation Plan

This plan details the implementation of the backend foundation for the VoltLife platform. It includes database models, Pydantic schemas, WebSocket management, background task pipelines, ML stubs, and API routes that strictly adhere to the VoltLife architecture.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Must-Fix #1 Applied:** The CSV parser, telemetry schema, and ML features wrapper are designed to accept 6 optional columns: `fade_rate`, `fade_acceleration`, `cv_phase_fraction`, `voltage_slope`, `voltage_variance`, and `discharge_efficiency`. When missing, they default to `NaN`, preventing errors while supporting full feature input.
>
> **Must-Fix #2 Applied:** In the predictor post-processing wrapper, `rul_cycles` will be clamped at `2400` (which is equivalent to 8.0 years × 300 cycles per year), ensuring consistency between energy unlocked calculations and the displayed RUL years.
>
> **Should-Fix #1 Applied (SQLite Fallback):** The database connection is built using generic SQLAlchemy types (`JSON` and `DateTime(timezone=True)`) to support both PostgreSQL and SQLite. In `sqlite://` databases, the tables will be created via `metadata.create_all()` at startup, skipping Alembic migrations automatically.
>
> **Autonomous Mode Flag (`AUTONOMY_MODE`):** The engine deployment approvals auto-advance to `approved` state when the autonomy mode is active (default for demo), and use a standard `recommended -> approved -> dispatched` workflow otherwise.

